Import Data

This is a very very ugly spreadsheet. The sample names and data are not really easily combined. I think Ill read them in separately and combine later?

LCMS data

lcms_data.raw <- read_excel(here("data", "raw", "Tea_LCMS_Report_050719.xlsx"), 
                        range = "C16:GF31")
New names:
* Conc -> Conc...11
* Flags -> Flags...12
* Conc -> Conc...13
* Flags -> Flags...14
* Conc -> Conc...15
*  and 171 more problems
lcms_data <-
  lcms_data.raw %>%
  slice(-1) %>% #remove blank row
  clean_names() %>% 
  select(-(2:10)) #get rid of compound metadata

Now capture sample names

sample_names <- read_excel(here("data", "raw", "Tea_LCMS_Report_050719.xlsx"), 
    range = "M4:GF5")
New names:
* blank -> blank...1
* `` -> ...2
* `` -> ...4
* `` -> ...6
* `` -> ...8
*  and 100 more problems
colnames(lcms_data) <- c("compound", colnames(sample_names))

get rid of flags columns and gather

lcms_tidy <-
  lcms_data %>% 
  select(-starts_with("...")) %>% #flags columns, not important
  gather(-compound, key = "sample", value = "conc") %>% 
  mutate(conc = as.numeric(conc)) %>%  #NAs are non-detects. need to deal with later.
  filter(!str_detect(sample, "blank"), !str_detect(sample, "Tea_Std")) #remove blanks and standards
NAs introduced by coercion

Create columns for cultivar and plant number

lcms_tidy <-
  lcms_tidy %>% 
  mutate(cultivar = str_extract(sample, "^\\D")) %>% 
  mutate(plant_num = str_extract(sample, "\\d+")) %>% 
  select(compound, sample, cultivar, plant_num, conc)

Deal with duplicates

For Q14Q20 the samples were run twice. Josh ran out of nitrogen for a few weeks and when he got more, he ran diluted samples that had been kept at -4 as well as new dilutions from samples that had been kept at -80. He said the -80 storage (Q##_2) look more similar to the other samples and I should probably use those. It looks like there was a storage effect for theanine, caffeine, and ECG (and maybe EGCG)

lcms_tidy %>% 
  filter(sample %in% c("Q14", "Q14_2", "Q15", "Q15_2", "Q16", "Q16_2", "Q17", "Q17_2", "Q18", "Q18_2", "Q19", "Q19_2", "Q20", "Q20_2")) %>% 
ggplot(aes(x = sample, y = conc)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~compound)

lcms_tidy <-
  lcms_tidy %>% 
  filter(!sample %in% c(paste0("Q", 14:20))) %>% 
  mutate(sample = str_remove(sample, "_\\d"))

Divide by leaf powder ammount

Joshs data is in g/mL and he said he accounted for the 10.1 dillution. We used about 20 mg for 1 mL for the extraction. So, to get g/mg should just have to divide by the sample amount (about 20mg).

To get g/mg tea leaf

sample_ammount_2017 <-
  read_csv(here("data", "raw", "2017QData - Sheet1.csv")) %>%
  clean_names() %>% 
  select(sample, mg_tea)
